<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="466" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,1319,1416]" pageId="15" pageNumber="466">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,1319,1344]" pageId="15" pageNumber="466">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The combination of a triangular and reflexed clypeus, mandibles without lateral teeth, and pronotum with a deep, longitudinal fovea easily distinguishes 
<taxonomicName box="[731,854,1356,1381]" class="Insecta" family="Dynastidae" genus="Oxyligyrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="466" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[731,854,1356,1381]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="466">Oxyligyrus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species from any other genera of 
<taxonomicName box="[1234,1381,1356,1381]" class="Insecta" family="Scarabaeidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="466" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Pentodontini">Pentodontini</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
